course_aims.value:
To develop the student's skills in the design and analysis of algorithms; 
To study algorithms for a range of important standard problems; 
To introduce the student to the theory of NP-completeness together with its practical implications;
To make the student aware of fundamental concepts of computability.

intended_learning_outcomes_of_course.value:
By the end of the course the student will be able to:
Recognise, and be able to use, standard algorithmic design methods;
Apply the basic principles of algorithm analysis;
Code standard efficient sorting algorithms;
Code fundamental graph algorithms - for search and traversal, shortest paths, minimum spanning trees, and topological sorting;
Describe classical algorithms for string searching, string comparison, and text compression;
Expound on the basic principles, and the practical implications of, the theory of NP-completeness;
Follow NP-completeness proofs for particular problems;
Deploy various strategies for dealing with computational problems that are apparently intractable;
Provide examples of the computability and unsolvability, and know some standard examples of unsolvable problems.
